{% extends "demo.html.j2" %}

{% block head_extra %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/pages/s1.css">
{% endblock %}

{% block demo_content %}
{% set ns = namespace(movers=0) %}
{% for m in card_data.managers %}
  {% if m.ols_rank != m.posterior_rank %}{% set ns.movers = ns.movers + 1 %}{% endif %}
{% endfor %}

<section class="ledger-intro">
  <p class="ledger-headline">
    Shrinking each manager toward their strategy peers reshuffles the ranking:
    <strong>{{ ns.movers }} of {{ card_data.meta.n_managers }} managers change rank</strong>
    under peer shrinkage and uncertainty-aware ordering. Each comparison starts from an
    ordinary least squares (OLS) estimate. This is a change in estimates, not proof that
    this roster's true-skill order improved.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="ledger-focal" aria-labelledby="ledger-focal-title">
  <div class="ledger-focal__intro">
    <p class="ledger-focal__eyebrow">Three managers explain the mechanism</p>
    <h2 id="ledger-focal-title">The same model can hold, lower, or raise a manager.</h2>
    <p>Start with these three cases before opening the full roster. The direction comes
      from the manager's estimate relative to the peer mean; the size of the move comes
      from how much evidence the track record earns.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="ledger-focal__grid">
    {% for code in ['A10', 'B10', 'A07'] %}
    {% set m = card_data.managers | selectattr('code', 'equalto', code) | first %}
    {% set delta = m.ols_rank - m.posterior_rank %}
    <article class="ledger-focal__card" data-focal-manager="{{ m.code }}">
      <header>
        <p class="ledger-focal__code">{{ m.months }} monthly observations</p>
        <h3>{{ m.name }}</h3>
      </header>
      <div class="ledger-focal__comparison">
        <p><span>Raw OLS alpha</span><strong>{{ "%+.1f"|format(m.ols_alpha.point * 100) }}%</strong></p>
        <span class="ledger-focal__arrow" aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        <p><span>Posterior alpha</span><strong>{{ "%+.1f"|format(m.posterior_alpha.point * 100) }}%</strong></p>
      </div>
      <p class="ledger-focal__rank">OLS #{{ m.ols_rank }} &rarr; posterior #{{ m.posterior_rank }}</p>
      <p class="ledger-focal__reading">
        {% if code == 'A10' %}
        A long, clean record earns enough weight to keep the leading estimate and rank.
        {% elif code == 'B10' %}
        A shorter record is pulled further toward peers, lowering the estimate and rank.
        {% else %}
        Shrinkage can also raise a manager whose raw estimate sits below its peer signal.
        {% endif %}
      </p>
    </article>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
</section>

<aside class="exhibit-guide" aria-label="What this exhibit shows">
  <h2 class="exhibit-guide__title">What this exhibit shows</h2>
  <p class="exhibit-guide__lead">
    <strong>What you are looking at.</strong> Each row is one manager's alpha
    shown twice &mdash; the raw OLS estimate and the posterior after it is shrunk
    toward its strategy peers. Osprey Hollow Partners leads on both: a raw
    +29.3% barely moves to +25.4% and holds rank #1, because a long, clean record
    is trusted. Cinderbank Capital instead falls from +19.6% (#3) to +13.2%
    (#4): its 36-month record earns a shrinkage weight of only 0.46, so the peer
    mean pulls it down. Across the roster, {{ ns.movers }} of
    {{ card_data.meta.n_managers }} managers change rank under peer shrinkage.
    This controlled synthetic example does not prove better true-skill recovery: its
    underlying ordering is slightly worse after shrinkage. Repeated-grid rank recovery
    and live calibration remain requirements.
  </p>
  <p class="exhibit-guide__subhead">How to read it</p>
  <ul class="exhibit-guide__map">
    <li><strong>Two interval bands per row</strong> &mdash; left is the OLS alpha,
      right is the posterior; each band is the 90% interval and the tick inside is
      the point estimate.</li>
    <li><strong>OLS #x &rarr; posterior #y and the &#9650;/&#9660; chip</strong>
      &mdash; rank before and after shrinkage; the chip flags rose, fell, or held,
      and movers carry an accent stripe down the left edge.</li>
    <li><strong>The band pill</strong> (review / minimum / standard / conviction)
      &mdash; the advisory capital band from the posterior t-ratio.</li>
    <li><strong>P(&alpha; &gt; 0)</strong> &mdash; the posterior probability true
      alpha is positive, capped at &gt;0.99 because certainty is never displayed.</li>
    <li>The full methodology &mdash; with the math and a reference implementation
      &mdash; is in
      <a href="{{ asset_base | default('') }}specs/{{ card.id }}.html">Technical method and provenance</a>.</li>
  </ul>
</aside>

<details class="ledger-roster">
  <summary>Explore all 20 managers</summary>
  <div class="ledger-controls">
    <button type="button" class="sort-toggle" data-sort-toggle data-order="ols">
      Order by: OLS rank
    </button>
    <span class="ledger-legend">
      <span class="rank-move rank-move--up">&#9650;</span> rose &middot;
      <span class="rank-move rank-move--down">&#9660;</span> fell after shrinkage
    </span>
  </div>
  <section class="ledger" data-ledger>
  {% for m in card_data.managers | sort(attribute='ols_rank') %}
  {% set delta = m.ols_rank - m.posterior_rank %}
  <article class="ledger-row{% if delta != 0 %} ledger-row--mover{% endif %}"
           data-ols-rank="{{ m.ols_rank }}"
           data-posterior-rank="{{ m.posterior_rank }}">
    <header class="ledger-row__head">
      <span class="ledger-row__code">{{ m.name }}</span>
      <span class="ledger-row__meta">group {{ m.group }} &middot; {{ m.months }} months</span>
      <span class="advisory-band" data-band="{{ m.advisory_band }}">{{ m.advisory_band }}</span>
    </header>

    <div class="ledger-row__ranks">
      <span class="rank-pair">OLS #{{ m.ols_rank }} &rarr; posterior #{{ m.posterior_rank }}</span>
      {% if delta > 0 %}
        <span class="rank-move rank-move--up">&#9650; {{ delta }}</span>
      {% elif delta < 0 %}
        <span class="rank-move rank-move--down">&#9660; {{ -delta }}</span>
      {% else %}
        <span class="rank-move rank-move--same">&mdash; held</span>
      {% endif %}
    </div>

    <div class="ledger-row__stats">
      <div class="interval-stat"
           data-lo="{{ m.ols_alpha.ci_lo }}"
           data-point="{{ m.ols_alpha.point }}"
           data-hi="{{ m.ols_alpha.ci_hi }}">
        <span class="interval-stat__label">OLS alpha (annual)</span>
        <span class="interval-stat__value">{{ "%+.1f"|format(m.ols_alpha.point * 100) }}%</span>
        <div class="interval-stat__rail">
          <div class="interval-stat__band"></div>
          <div class="interval-stat__point"></div>
        </div>
        <span class="interval-stat__range">90% interval {{ "%+.1f"|format(m.ols_alpha.ci_lo * 100) }}% &hellip; {{ "%+.1f"|format(m.ols_alpha.ci_hi * 100) }}%</span>
      </div>

      <div class="interval-stat"
           data-lo="{{ m.posterior_alpha.ci_lo }}"
           data-point="{{ m.posterior_alpha.point }}"
           data-hi="{{ m.posterior_alpha.ci_hi }}">
        <span class="interval-stat__label">Posterior alpha (annual)</span>
        <span class="interval-stat__value">{{ "%+.1f"|format(m.posterior_alpha.point * 100) }}%</span>
        <div class="interval-stat__rail">
          <div class="interval-stat__band"></div>
          <div class="interval-stat__point"></div>
        </div>
        <span class="interval-stat__range">90% interval {{ "%+.1f"|format(m.posterior_alpha.ci_lo * 100) }}% &hellip; {{ "%+.1f"|format(m.posterior_alpha.ci_hi * 100) }}%</span>
      </div>

      <div class="ledger-row__prob">
        <span class="interval-stat__label">P(&alpha; &gt; 0)</span>
        {# Doctrine: never display certainty — 1.0 in the JSON is 6-digit rounding. #}
        <span class="ledger-row__prob-value">{% if m.prob_positive > 0.99 %}&gt;0.99{% elif m.prob_positive < 0.01 %}&lt;0.01{% else %}{{ "%.2f"|format(m.prob_positive) }}{% endif %}</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
  {% endfor %}
  </section>
</details>

<p class="ledger-footnote">
  This gallery page uses the closed-form normal&ndash;normal shrinkage variant
  (empirical-Bayes moment estimates per strategy group). A production implementation
  would use the full hierarchical MCMC model &mdash; the displayed formula teaches the
  intuition rather than certifying a deployable result. See Technical method and
  provenance &sect;3.7.
</p>
<p class="ledger-footnote"><strong>Evidence boundary.</strong> This synthetic roster shows how
  peer shrinkage changes estimates, intervals, and order. It does not establish better
  true-skill recovery, predictive accuracy, or live calibration.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block methodology %}
<p>Each manager's raw OLS alpha is shrunk toward their strategy-group mean by the
weight their track length earns: a short, noisy record is pulled hard toward the
peer mean; a long, clean record barely moves. The band shown is the 90% interval;
a bare point alpha is never shown without it.</p>
<p>Shrinkage never claims &ldquo;your alpha was cut&rdquo; &mdash; it reports
&ldquo;shrunk toward strategy peers by the weight your track length earns.&rdquo;
The resulting order is uncertainty-aware, but its true-skill recovery must clear the
repeated-grid and live-calibration gates before it informs ranking decisions.</p>
{% endblock %}

{% block body_scripts %}
<script src="{{ asset_base | default('') }}assets/s1-ledger.js"></script>
{% endblock %}
